Background and Motivation¶

Question: Does an individuals parents educational background play the most significant role in how well they performs on standardized tests? Are there other factors that might have a more significant impact?

Standardized testing is a very important factor in every student's life, no matter what career path they choose to take. It follows them everywhere, starting from high school. Getting a strong SAT score plays about 50% of most college's decisions in whether or not to accept a student into their school. There has always been contreversial disucssions that take place with how fair standardized testing really is, given that students may perform well depending on different factors such as their background, their race, how financially stable their family is, and how well they are supported in their education. Getting into a good college plays a huge role in how educated a person enters the "real world" and what they can offer to society. Being that stardized testing plays an important role in who gets into which college, it became a highlighted issue to research into. After coming across this dataset, curiosity was sparked to find out if any of factors really do play a role in how well students do in standardized tests, specifcally speaking if a parent's background plays the most significant role.

Methodology¶

First, in order to know what was being dealt with, we displayed the data set by using a simple pd.read_csv command using the pandas dataframe. After doing so, we were able to see all the different columns of the dataset and the diferent data that had been collected. After displaying the data, we used the .describe() function to get a basic idea of the statistics of the data, such as the minimum, maximum, 25%, 50% (median), and 75% percentiles in student's math, reading, and writing scores of standardized tests.

To begin with, we use a more basic method to get a general understanding of the comparison between the parental levels education and test scores using scatter plots. Understanding the scatter plot for the parental level of education was more difficult that expected, as there were mutliple different categories being compared within.

In order to do this, 3 subplots were created, where we set the test scores to different axes ('x' and 'y') in each subplot to get variations of comparisons of the data:

1st subplot --> student's parent's education level vs student's reading vs. writing scores
2nd subplot --> student's parent's education level vs student's reading vs. math scores
3rd subplot --> student's parent's education level vs student's writing vs. math scores

Then we set a 'data' variable to set each seperate scatter plot to a different level of education

high_school_complete = 0
high_school_none = 0

college_none = 0

bachelor_none = 0

assoicates_complete = 0
assoicates_none = 0

masters_complete = 0
masters_none = 0

total_list = []

education_testprep = stu_performance[["parental level of education","test preparation course"]]

for i in range(len(education_testprep)):
        total_list.append(education_testprep.iloc[i])
for i in total_list:
    if i[0] == "high school" and i[1] == "completed":
        high_school_complete += 1
    elif i[0] == "high school" and i[1] == "none":
        high_school_none += 1
        
    if i[0] == "some college" and i[1] == "completed":
        college_complete += 1
    elif i[0] == "some college" and i[1] == "none":
        college_none += 1
        
    elif i[0] == "bachelor's degree" and i[1] == "completed":
        bachelor_complete += 1
    elif i[0] == "bachelor's degree" and i[1] == "none":
        bachelor_none += 1
        
    elif i[0] == "associate's degree" and i[1] == "completed":
        assoicates_complete += 1
    elif i[0] == "associate's degree" and i[1] == "none":
        assoicates_none += 1
        
    elif i[0] == "master's degree" and i[1] == "completed":
        masters_complete += 1
    elif i[0] == "master's degree" and i[1] == "none":
        masters_none += 1


completance = ["high school", "some college", "bachelor's degree", "associate's degree", "master's"]
completed= [high_school_complete, college_complete, bachelor_complete, assoicates_complete, masters_complete]
none = [high_school_none, college_none, bachelor_none, assoicates_none, masters_none]

hist_length = np.arange(len(completance))

plt.ylabel('Number of Students')
plt.xticks(hist_length,completance)
plt.title("Number of Students vs. Amount of Test Preperation")

Here, we used a barplots in order to compare 1) each of the possible education level's of student's parents to whether or not the student completed a test preperation course 2) each of the possible education level's of student's parents to whether or not the student recieved a standard lunch plan or a reduced/free lunch plan.

Figuring out how to display the histogram with more than one bar was somewhat of a difficult task. Knowing how to get the data of which students didn't complete the test preperation course and which ones did wasn't hard, but knowing how to seperate the students by their parent's educational level was what made the process tricky. Figuring which method was most efficient to use was time consuming and a process of trial and error.

First we seperated the dataset by creating a new varibale that would only hold two specific columns from the original dataset, "parental level of education" and "test preparation course". Then we looped through the variable and seperated the columns by using the .iloc function before appending them into a list. Then we looped through the new list where we used the index to seperate the lists, using if statements, by parental level of education, and then whether or not the student completed a test preperation course. The usage of .iloc made it very simple to index through the values, which took the most time to figure out how to use. Repeating this process for lunch types was simple, as we used the same technique, only used the "lunch" column instead.

At the end of our code, we have some print statements that allowed us to see the ratios of 1) how many students in each seperate parental education level either completed or didn't complete the test preperation course over the total number of students in each seperate parental education level 2) how many students in each seperate parental education level either recieved standard lunch plan or free/reduced lunch plan over the total number of students in each seperate parental education level:

1) (# of students "completed" test preperation / total students of one of the parental education levels)
2)  (# of students "none" test preperation / total students of one of the parental education levels)

3) (# of students with "standard" lunch type / total students of specific parental education levels)
4) (# of students with "reduced/free" lunch type / total students of specific parental education levels)

We used this final method in order to see if how the ratios correlated in comparision to the levels of parental education. We wanted to know if the ratios of having completed a test preperation course and of having a standard lunch plan were greater than the ratios of not completing a test preperation course and having a free/reduced lunch plan

In this section we have a group of box plot charts above, we decided to use a dataframe that was unfamiliar to us: seaborn. Using the seaborn datafram made it simple to create boxplots using differnt aspects of data.

In order to use the box plots from the dataframe, we first created 3 subplots in order to get the data from all 3 test scores. We then set an 'x' variable to equal a different aspect of data in each boxplot set (race, education leve, gender, lunch plan, etc.) and 'y' to be the three different test score types (math, reading, or writing). This way we were able to compare each aspect of the different data categories to the different kinds of test scores. Boxplots are also helpful in getting a general idea of the data in whichever aspect you choose to analyze in, such as seeing the maximum, minimum values, and the median.

As mentioned before, the scatter plot results were somewhat difficult to comprehend due to the multiple levels of education. From what we can see, towards the most upper right end of the scatter plot, towards the main colors we see are purple, green, and yellow, which happen to be the data for "bachelor's", "assoiciate's", and "master's" degree. Towards the bottom left, where the score values are much lower, the range mainly consists of the colors red and blue which happen to be the data for "high school" and "some college" which are of the lower levels of parental education. This allows us to infer that there may be some significant correlation to a student's parent's level of education. However, since the data is very much scattered through out the ranges, it shows that students with parent's who had a "lower" level of education still performed well, and some of students with parent's who had a "higher" level of education perfromed less well.

Within the boxplots above, we were able to learn a few things:

  1) First off, from the last boxplot presented, we can see that students with parent(s) who have a education level
     of "master's" degree show to have best result in all three test score types, as well as having the highest
     25%, 50%,  and 75% quartiles of the three test score types. We can see that as the levels of education get lower,            
     the boxplot results either decrease,or stay the same. Therefore it is correct to say that parental levels of      
     education play a role in how well their kids do in standardized tests

 2)  Gender may play a role in how high test scores are, as from the first box plot we can see that women did quite      
     better in reading and writing than men did, with higher 25%, 50%, and 75% quartiles, while men did better in
     math than women did ith higher 25%, 50%, and 75% quartiles as well.

 3)  Having completed test prepartion did indeed play a role in how high test scores are, as we can see that in all  
     three test score categories, those who completed a test preperation course did better than those who did not 
     complete a test preperation course, with fairly higher 25%, 50%, and 75% quartiles.

 4) Finally, ethnicity also may play a role in how high test scores are as well, as we can see that ethinicity
    "Group E" did better in all three types of test scores, with higher 25%, 50%, and 75% quartiles in all three types            
    of test scores as well.

Discussion and Conclusion¶

From our results, it can be said that having parent(s) with a higher level of education can be highly considered in the factors of how well a student does in standardized tests. This can be for many reasons, one that parents with higher education levels may have better jobs than student's parents with lower levels of education, meaning they are making more money and can support their kids with test preperation courses, which can be pricey, and any additional resources needed to succeed. However, there are other significant factors as well, such as gender and ethnicity as we could see that "ethnicity E" had higher results in every test score type, and women did better than men in reading and writing, and men did better than women in math. There could be so many other factors that, in the end, effect how well a student does in their standardized tests, and their parent's education level is a major one to consider.

Some obstacles that were faced were not knowing how to split the data when we wanted to search and compare different columns of the dataset, rather than the whole set. This was solved after knowing how to use the iloc[] function. Something that could be done differently is implementing the usage of more analyzing the future data, which was difficult with how this dataset was set up. Something else that could have been done additionaly, instead of differntly, was getting the ratio values of the students who did and didn't complete standardized testing with eachother (high school complete/ high school none), so we could analyze the number of students numerically, knowing how many times better they would do. Did they do 2 or 3 times better? 1/2 times better?
